I disagree with Mr. Margulies.  Seems to me that if you know what
domains you will need in the future it is much easier to set them
up now.  Then when the change comes you merely split the database
into a few pieces, set up some new servers, and change a few
pointers to these servers.  If you change the whole structure of
your subdomain in the future, your hosts will all have new names
and you'll have a bit more work to do in setting up the servers
with appropriate pointers between levels in your new domain
hierarchy.

It's easy to say "the - can turn into a ." but I think this will
mean a lot more work.
